The paper discusses the statistical properties of citation-based indicators used to evaluate the impact of scholarly outputs. This topic is relevant to several sub-categories in computer science, including Information Retrieval (cs.IR), Digital Libraries (cs.DL), Social and Information Networks (cs.SI), Cryptography and Security (cs.CR), and Computers and Society (cs.CY). However, given that the paper focuses on subject-specific journals, it is most likely to belong to the Information Retrieval (cs.IR) sub-category, which deals with the retrieval of information from large collections of data, including scholarly publications.
